2682. 64. Scripsi] The letter to George Paungartner is Ep. 2683; that to John Chrysostom is not ex- tant.

Ioanni Chrysostomo] Panfilo Zanco (1490 '3—1566), son of Paul Zanco, was born at Bergamo, of an ancient family. Becoming a canon regular in 1524 he took the names John chrysostom. In 1529 he was sent by his Order to Padua; meeting there both Bern bo and Viglius (Bembo he had already known in Bergamo where Bembo's father had been ‘ podesta'). Four years later he moved to Ravenna (see Ep. 2885). On 25 Feb. 1536 Viglius addresses a letter to him at Ravenna, VZE p. 206: from a letter of Aretinus (and from

- Zanco’s reply) we know that he was

still there in 1540 (Aret. Epp. 1 1. 150). In that year he was appointed Prior of the Holy Spirit at Bergarno. In 1559 he became General of his Order, dying seven years later in his native town. In, or before, 1536 he pub·

In 1541 he printed at Venice, and dedicated to Bembo, his principal work De Orobiorum siue Cenomanorum oriqine situ ac Beryarni rebus antiquis libri iii. He wrote also a number of Greek and Latin verses, which he did not print. In 1532 he sent an elegy on the death of his father, with other poems, to Viglius, who passed thern on to Logus (Brussels MS.
